  "texts": [
    "This implies, together with the fact from above that h is a robust possibility morphism, that h is a ⊑-strong embedding.",
    "This proof provides an example of how our ⊑-back clause may apply when the standard back clause for a p-morphism does not, i.e., Y ⊑ ′℘ h(x) does not imply there is a y ⊑ x such that h(y) = Y, as required by a p-morphism.",
    "For if all we assume is that F is atomic, there is no guarantee that for each set Y of minimal points in F, there is a y in F such that the set of minimal points refining y, our h(y) above, is exactly Y.In § 4.7, we will identify the possibility frames F for which (AtF) ℘ is isomorphic to F. Extended FramesWhen we defined the powerset possibilization of a world frame (Example 2.9), we chopped off the bottom element ∅ of the poset ⟨℘(W), ⊆⟩.",
    "However, it would sometimes be convenient-especially when dealing with the functional frames of § 4.4 or the principal frames of § 4.6-to allow in our frames a distinguished minimum element ⊥, which may be thought of as the \"impossible state.",
    "\"To be clear: a possibility frame as in Definition 2.21 is already allowed to have a minimum in its poset ⟨S, ⊑⟩, but such frames are somewhat uninteresting for the following reason."
